Wash and dry produce.

Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1} into strips. Drain and rinse @black beans{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a small #pot{} over medium-high heat. Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup} and half the @tomato paste{1}(half for 4 servings). Cook, stirring, until rice is evenly coated, ~{30-60%seconds} more.

Add @water{1%cup} (2 cups for 4), @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. (You'll use the rest of the Southwest Spice Blend later.) Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Turn off heat and keep covered until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper; cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with salt and @pepper{}.

Add beans, @Tex-Mex paste{1}, remaining @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}, and @water{1/4%cup}. Cook, stirring, until filling is combined and thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> Pat chicken dry with paper towels. Add chicken or beef to pan along with green pepper; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, until beef or chicken is browned and cooked through, 4-6 minutes. (TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.) Cook through the rest of the step as directed.

Add @ground beef{10%ounce} to pan; cook, stirring frequently, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

In a small #bowl{}, combine @vegan mayo{4%tbsp}, cilantro, and a pinch of salt and pepper. Add water, 1 tsp at a time, until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}. Wrap @flour tortillas{2} in damp paper towels and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Lay tortillas on a clean work surface. Add as much rice, bean filling, and as much @pico de gallo{4%ounce} as you like across the bottom third of tortillas. Drizzle with as much creamy cilantro sauce as you like.

Fold bottom edge of each tortilla over filling, then fold over left and right sides toward the filling. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to form wraps.

Halve wraps on a diagonal; divide between plates along with any remaining rice, bean filling, and pico de gallo. Serve with any remaining cilantro sauce on the side for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.